  abstract = {This work presents an approach to assessing the impact of a diverse set of water-resource-related projects that are funded by NASA's Western Water Applications Office (WWAO). WWAO's mission is to help solve important and pressing water-resource problems that the western United States faces today. Each of its projects is designed to advance WWAO's mission by equipping water decision-makers with useful, accessible and sustained remote-sensing-based information. Conducting an impact assessment that can be applied to a range of applied-science projects is challenging. It involves designing a process that is flexible and customizable to each specific project, but that also provides information that can be synthesized across all projects in order to enable WWAO to evaluate the overall performance of its program. This talk will discuss our impact assessment methodology, which includes (1) understanding the stakeholder's decision-making context; (2) isolating which decision the project aims to support within that context; and (3) identifying the key outcomes that the improved decision-making process will deliver. The level of quantification of these impacts varies by project, ranging from an "impact story"-which includes unquantified outcomes traced within the stakeholder decision-making context - to a full value-of-information (VOI) assessment-which quantifies the monetary benefit of one or more socioeconomically-relevant outcomes. The impact assessment methodology emphasizes five outcome focus areas, with an ultimate goal of the WWAO program making a positive societal impact in each one: ecological benefits, water savings, social benefits, climate resilience, local economic benefits, and institutional cost savings. Through identifying desired long-term impacts and outcomes in the first phase of project formulation, we recognize a potential for transforming a business-as-usual "push" method, which implies developing a tool or service without understanding the